{"CoRequisites": [], "CreditType": "", "Credits": "3.00", "CrossListed": "N", "DepartmentID": "43", "Departments": "EN Applied Mathematics & Statistics", "Description": "This biennial course covers topics in the theory, methods, and applications of machine learning from an explicitly statistical perspective.

Recommended Course Background: (EN.550.420 OR EN.553.420 OR EN.553.620) AND (EN.550.430 OR EN.553.430 OR EN.553.630)", "Equivalencies": [], "EvaluationUrls": [], "Fees": [], "GradeSystemName": "AE Grad Letter", "InstructionMethods": "In-person", "Instructors": [{"HopkinsID": "9YDMXJ"}], "Meetings": [{"Building": "Remsen Hall", "DOW": "MW", "Dates": "01-21-2025 to 04-28-2025", "Format": "Lecture", "Times": "04:30 PM - 05:45 PM"}], "PosTags": [], "PrereqCoursesCatalogs": [], "Prerequisites": [], "Restrictions": [{"Description": "", "RestrictionName": "Grad students"}], "SampleSyllabus": "", "SectionCoReqNotes": "", "SectionCoRequisites": "", "StandardSyllabusLink": "", "TextbookInformations": [{"AttributeValue": "Barnes & Noble", "BookstoreID": "", "ClassStartDate": "20250121", "CourseName": "EN.553.739", "CourseNumber": "", "Department": "", "IdrGroupTerm": "W25", "Location": "Homewood Campus", "MbsGroupDesignator": "", "MbsSiteCode": "", "Name": "01", "SectionNumber": "", "Term": "", "ZonesName": "ASEN - UGrad"}], "WebNotes": "Enrollment restricted to AMS Department graduate students, MSEM Operations Research students and MSEM Probability and Statistics students for two weeks. Open to graduates only after two weeks. 
"}

{"CoRequisites": [], "CreditType": "", "Credits": "3.00", "CrossListed": "N", "DepartmentID": "43", "Departments": "EN Applied Mathematics & Statistics", "Description": "Probabilistic machine learning harnesses the power of probability theory to provide models for complex data, as well as the algorithms that enable learning, inference, sampling, and decision-making for these models. The first part of the course will cover classical approaches based on directed and undirected probabilistic graphical models, including latent variable models and temporal models. We develop a toolkit of algorithms used for learning and inference, including message passing algorithms, Markov chain Monte Carlo, and variational inference. Building on these foundational ideas, the second part of the course will cover modern (deep learning) approaches to generative modeling such as variational auto-encoders, generative adversarial networks, normalizing flows, and diffusion models. A background in machine learning is recommended.", "Equivalencies": [], "EvaluationUrls": [], "Fees": [], "GradeSystemName": "AE Grad Letter", "InstructionMethods": "In-person", "Instructors": [{"HopkinsID": "6C2DA0"}], "Meetings": [{"Building": "Maryland", "DOW": "MW", "Dates": "01-21-2025 to 04-28-2025", "Format": "Lecture", "Times": "03:00 PM - 04:15 PM"}], "PosTags": [], "PrereqCoursesCatalogs": [{"Description": "Probability and its applications, at the calculus level. Emphasis on techniques of application and on rigorous mathematical demonstration.  Probability, combinatorial probability, random variables, distribution functions, important probability distributions, independence, conditional probability, moments, covariance and correlation, limit theorems.  Students initiating graduate work in probability or statistics should enroll in EN.553.620 or EN.553.720.  Prerequisites: one year of calculus.  Corequisites: multivariable calculus and linear algebra.

Students who have received credit for AS.110.106 and/or AS.110.107 taken prior to Fall 2020 should contact the course instructor to determine whether they can receive permission to register for this course.", "Name": "EN.553.420", "SssCoursesId": 39352, "StatusName": "Active", "TermName": "AE Spring 2025", "Title": "Probability"}, {"Description": "Probability and its applications, at the calculus level. Emphasis on techniques of application and on rigorous mathematical demonstration. Probability, combinatorial probability, random variables, distribution functions, important probability distributions, independence, conditional probability, moments, covariance and correlation, limit theorems.  Recommended course background: (AS.110.109 or  AS.110.113) and previously or concurrently (AS.110.202 or AS.110.201 or AS.110.212).", "Name": "EN.553.620", "SssCoursesId": 39380, "StatusName": "Active", "TermName": "AE Spring 2025", "Title": "Probability"}, {"Description": "The course objectives are to develop probabilistic reasoning and problem solving approaches, to provide a rigorous mathematical basis for probability theory, and to examine several important results in the theory of probability. Topics include axiomatic probability, independence, random variables and their distributions, expectation, integration, variance and moments, probability inequalities, and modes of convergence of random variables. The course will include introductory measure theory as needed. Students are expected to have previous study of both analysis and probability. This course is the first half of a yearlong sequence. The second semester’s course, EN.553.721 Probability Theory II, will cover classical limit theorems, characteristic functions, and conditional expectation.  Prerequisite: real analysis (AS.110.405/AS.110.415)", "Name": "EN.553.720", "SssCoursesId": 39376, "StatusName": "Active", "TermName": "AE Spring 2025", "Title": "Probability Theory I"}], "Prerequisites": [{"Description": "EN.553.420 OR EN.553.620 OR EN.553.720", "Expression": "EN.553.420[C]^OR^EN.553.620[C]^OR^EN.553.720[C]", "IsNegative": "N"}], "Restrictions": [{"Description": "", "RestrictionName": "Grad students"}], "SampleSyllabus": "", "SectionCoReqNotes": "", "SectionCoRequisites": "", "StandardSyllabusLink": "", "TextbookInformations": [{"AttributeValue": "Barnes & Noble", "BookstoreID": "", "ClassStartDate": "20250121", "CourseName": "EN.553.724", "CourseNumber": "", "Department": "", "IdrGroupTerm": "W25", "Location": "Homewood Campus", "MbsGroupDesignator": "", "MbsSiteCode": "", "Name": "01", "SectionNumber": "", "Term": "", "ZonesName": "ASEN - UGrad"}], "WebNotes": "Enrollment restricted to AMS Department graduate students, MSEM Operations Research students and MSEM Probability and Statistics students for two weeks. Open to graduates only after two weeks. 
"}

{"CoRequisites": [], "CreditType": "", "Credits": "4.00", "CrossListed": "N", "DepartmentID": "43", "Departments": "EN Applied Mathematics & Statistics", "Description": "Introduction to the mathematics of finite systems. Logic; Boolean algebra; induction and recursion; sets, functions, relations, equivalence, and partially ordered sets; elementary combinatorics; modular arithmetic and the Euclidean algorithm; polynomials rings, group theory; permutations groups and Galois theory; graph theory. Selected applications. The concept of a proof and development of the ability to recognize and construct proofs and analyze algorithms are part of the course. Recommended Course Background: Four years of high school mathematics.", "Equivalencies": [], "EvaluationUrls": [], "Fees": [], "GradeSystemName": "AE Ugrad Letter", "InstructionMethods": "In-person", "Instructors": [{"HopkinsID": "ABBDCD|ABBDCD"}], "Meetings": [{"Building": "Hodson", "DOW": "MWF", "Dates": "01-21-2025 to 04-28-2025", "Format": "Lecture", "Times": "09:00 AM - 09:50 AM"}, {"Building": "Maryland", "DOW": "Th", "Dates": "01-21-2025 to 04-28-2025", "Format": "Discussion Section", "Times": "09:00 AM - 09:50 AM"}], "PosTags": [], "PrereqCoursesCatalogs": [{"Description": "Introduction to the mathematics of finite systems. Logic; Boolean algebra; induction and recursion; sets, functions, relations, equivalence, and partially ordered sets; elementary combinatorics; modular arithmetic and the Euclidean algorithm; group theory; permutations and symmetry groups; graph theory. Selected applications. The concept of a proof and development of the ability to recognize and construct proofs are part of the course. Recommended Course Background: Four years of high school mathematics.", "Name": "EN.553.171", "SssCoursesId": 39339, "StatusName": "Active", "TermName": "AE Spring 2025", "Title": "Discrete Mathematics"}, {"Description": "This course provides an introduction to mathematical reasoning and discrete structures relevant to computer science. Topics include propositional and predicate logic, proof techniques including mathematical induction, sets, relations, functions, recurrences, counting techniques, simple computational models, asymptotic analysis, discrete probability, graphs, trees, and number theory.", "Name": "EN.601.230", "SssCoursesId": 44204, "StatusName": "Active", "TermName": "AE Spring 2025", "Title": "Mathematical Foundations for Computer Science"}, {"Description": "Counting techniques: generating functions, recurrence relations, Polya’s theorem. Combinatorial designs: Latin squares, finite geometries, balanced incomplete block designs. Emphasis on problem solving. Recommended Course Background: AS.553.291 or AS.110.201

Students who have received credit for AS.110.106 and/or AS.110.107 taken prior to Fall 2020 should contact the course instructor to determine whether they can receive permission to register for this course.", "Name": "EN.553.471", "SssCoursesId": 39348, "StatusName": "Active", "TermName": "AE Spring 2025", "Title": "Combinatorial Analysis"}, {"Description": "Study of systems of “vertices” with some pairs joined by “edges.” Theory of adjacency, connectivity, traversability, feedback, and other concepts underlying properties important in engineering and the sciences. Topics include paths, cycles, and trees; routing problems associated with Euler and Hamilton; design of graphs realizing specified incidence conditions and other constraints. Attention directed toward problem solving, algorithms, and applications. One or more topics taken up in greater depth.", "Name": "EN.553.472", "SssCoursesId": 39616, "StatusName": "Active", "TermName": "AE Spring 2025", "Title": "Graph Theory"}, {"Description": "An introduction to combinatorial analysis at the graduate level. Meets concurrently with 553.471. Counting techniques: generating functions, recurrence relations, Polya’s theorem. Combinatorial designs: Latin squares, finite geometries, balanced incomplete block designs. Emphasis on problem solving. Recommended Course Background: EN.553.291 or AS.110.201", "Name": "EN.553.671", "SssCoursesId": 39789, "StatusName": "Active", "TermName": "AE Spring 2025", "Title": "Combinatorial Analysis"}, {"Description": "Study of systems of “vertices” with some pairs joined by “edges.” Theory of adjacency, connectivity, traversability, feedback, and other concepts underlying properties important in engineering and the sciences. Topics include paths, cycles, and trees; routing problems associated with Euler and Hamilton; design of graphs realizing specified incidence conditions and other constraints. Attention directed toward problem solving, algorithms, and applications. One or more topics taken up in greater depth. Recommended Course Background: (EN.553.291 OR AS.110.201 OR AS.110.212)", "Name": "EN.553.672", "SssCoursesId": 39627, "StatusName": "Active", "TermName": "AE Spring 2025", "Title": "Graph Theory"}], "Prerequisites": [{"Description": "Students may only earn credit for one of the following: EN.553.171, EN.553.172, OR EN.601.230.
EN.553.172 may not be taken after EN.553.471 OR EN.553.472 OR EN.553.671 OR EN.553.672.", "Expression": "EN.553.171[C]^OR^EN.601.230[C]^OR^EN.553.471[C]^OR^EN.553.472[C]^OR^EN.553.671[C]^OR^EN.553.672[C]", "IsNegative": "Y"}], "Restrictions": [{"Description": "", "RestrictionName": "UGrad Applied Mathematics and Statistics majors"}, {"Description": "", "RestrictionName": "Applied Mathematics and Statistics minors"}], "SampleSyllabus": "", "SectionCoReqNotes": "", "SectionCoRequisites": "", "StandardSyllabusLink": "", "TextbookInformations": [{"AttributeValue": "Barnes & Noble", "BookstoreID": "", "ClassStartDate": "20250121", "CourseName": "EN.553.172", "CourseNumber": "", "Department": "", "IdrGroupTerm": "W25", "Location": "Homewood Campus", "MbsGroupDesignator": "", "MbsSiteCode": "", "Name": "01", "SectionNumber": "", "Term": "", "ZonesName": "ASEN - UGrad"}], "WebNotes": ""}

